f9a7c81b-f6b2-4595-b8e7-30784ac95910.4a27a719-e5c2-4d79-81a4-5f5959501690.description=
Searches for VMWare objects containing a given name (ignoring case). Retrieves each object one at a time from an initial search query as the one used for the SQL Query operation.

Inputs\:
    host - VMWare host hostname or IP.
    user - VMWare username.
    password - VMWare user's password.
    port - Port to connect on.
    protocol - Connection protocol.
Valid values\: "https", "http"
    closeSession - Close the internally kept VMware Infrastructure API session at completion of operation.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    propsType - VMWare properties type to filter on. Type of object results desired.
Example\: VirtualMachine, Network, ComputeResource, ClusterComputeResource, ResourcePool, HostSystem, Datastore, Datacenter, VirtualApp
    nameToMatch - The string to perform a case insensitive contains match to. Only objects that contain this string in their name will be matched.  If not specified, all objects of the specified type will be matched.
    connectionTimeout -  The time to wait for a connection to be established, in seconds. A "connectionTimeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
Format\: an integer representing seconds
Examples\: 10, 20
    socketTimeout -  The time to wait for data (a maximum period of inactivity between two consecutive data packets), in seconds. A "socketTimeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
Format\: an integer representing seconds
Examples\: 10, 20

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary result. It contains the query result item from the current iteration, a message if there are no more items to be retrieved or an error message otherwise.
    numberOfResults - This contains the number of results from the query remaining to be retrieved.
    returnCode - It contains the value 0 if the operation successfully completed but there are still more items to be retrieved, the value 1, if the operation successfully completed and there are no more items to be retrieved and the value -1 if an error occurred.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed successfully and there are more results available.
    failure - Something went wrong.
    no more - There are no more results to retrieve.
f9a7c81b-f6b2-4595-b8e7-30784ac95910.4dcb88a2-5057-44b7-a049-fae6057e3ba2.description=
This operation iterates through a list of values. It is not recommended to modify the value of the "list" and "separator" inputs during the iteration process.

Inputs\:
    list - The list to iterate through.
    separator - A delimiter separating the list elements.
Default value\: ‘,’ (comma) 

Results\:
    resultString - The current list element (if the response is "has more").

Responses\:
    has more - Another value was found in the list and it has been returned.
    no more - The iterator has gone through the entire list. This response is returned once per list iteration.  A subsequent call to the List iterator operation restarts the list iteration process.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
   The position of the iterator in the list is tracked by each step's unique identifier. Therefore, you can simultaneously iterate through the same list from multiple steps.

f9a7c81b-f6b2-4595-b8e7-30784ac95910.b8519f78-0fed-4154-88a7-536f7d439d87.description=
Retrieve information about a virtual machine or a set of virtual machines in a datacenter or host system. Retrieve each object one at a time from an initial search query as the one used in the SQL Query operation.

Inputs\:
    host - VMware vCenter, ESX or ESXi host hostname or IP.
    user - VMware username.
    password - VMware user's password.
    port - Port to connect on.
Examples\: 443, 80
    protocol - Connection protocol.
Valid values\: "https", "http"
    closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    vmDatacenter - Datacenter to get virtual machines from.
    hostSystem - Host system to get virtual machines from.
    vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type.  Required if virtualMachine input is used.
Valid values\: "inventorypath", "name", "ip", "hostname", "uuid", "vmid"
    virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. Inventorypath (Datacenter/vm/Folder/MyVM), Name of VM, IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123).
    getDetailed - Retrieve detailed information?
Valid Values\: true, false
    connectionTimeout -  The time to wait for a connection to be established, in seconds. A "connectionTimeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
Format\: an integer representing seconds
Examples\: 10, 20
    socketTimeout -  The time to wait for data (a maximum period of inactivity between two consecutive data packets), in seconds. A "socketTimeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
Format\: an integer representing seconds
Examples\: 10, 20

Results
    returnResult - Virtual machine ID (vmid) or reason for failure.
    vmInfo - Detailed virtual machine information when getDetailed is true.  Properties in this result are pipe delimited.
    numberOfResults - Number of results from the query remaining to be retrieved.
    name - Name of the virtual machine.
    uuid - UUID of the virtual machine.
    inventoryPath - Inventory path of the virtual machine.
    dataStore - The name of the datastore where the vm configuration file (.vmx) is stored.
    vmxPath - The path to the vm configuration file (.vmx) on dataStore.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.  See returnResult for details.
    no more - There are no more results to retrieve.

Notes\:
1) Depending on the "host" input value, the inventory path can have one of the following formats\: 
    - If "host" is an ESX server, the inventory path will have the format\: ha-datacenter/vm/
    - If "host" is a vCenter, the inventory path will have the format\: /vm// . The / part of the path is based on the "Virtual Machines & Templates" view in the vCenter client. 
2) The inventory path is case sensitive.
